When I joined RStudio 10 years ago, it was a very different world.

00:03:49.279 --> 00:03:53.160
A lot of people didn't know about R, or if they did, they had these impressions of R

00:03:53.160 --> 00:03:55.679
that were not very complimentary.

00:03:55.679 --> 00:03:58.919
So we had to spread the word about R, and we decided to do that by teaching people to

00:03:58.919 --> 00:04:03.440
use R in the tidyverse, which we were creating at workshops.

00:04:03.440 --> 00:04:10.279
We also experimented with other partners to do video courses, online courses, MOOCs.

00:04:10.279 --> 00:04:13.639
If there's a way to teach data science, I have done that.

00:04:13.639 --> 00:04:16.359
And if you think of someone who teaches data science, there's a good chance I might even

00:04:16.359 --> 00:04:20.359
work with them to help them do that as a partnership.

00:04:20.359 --> 00:04:24.640
And the reason there's nothing on this slide right now is because I want to talk about

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:29.040
some of the negative experiences, and I don't want to associate that with anyone in particular.

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:35.279
But what I quickly noticed teaching data science was that teachers out there really aren't

00:04:35.279 --> 00:04:36.279
that good.

00:04:36.279 --> 00:04:39.799
The workshops you see at conferences are not so great.

00:04:39.799 --> 00:04:44.040
And even some of the online courses, I really questioned how effective they would be.

00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:49.160
And after thinking about this, I realized the people who become experts at coding or

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:54.880
data science did that by devoting years of their life to becoming that expert.

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:58.720
But they didn't have a chance to devote those years to being a good teacher, or even find

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:01.920
out what made teaching work.

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:06.440
Serendipitously, my background is in psychology.

00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:11.440
I have a PhD in statistics, but that's from doing psychological research, I work my way

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:16.839
over to writing code that supports statistics, and now what we call data science.

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:20.839
And my background in psychology alerted me to the fact that there's many things that

00:05:20.839 --> 00:05:26.760
you can do to make training more successful, and I thought, well, there's these theories

00:05:26.760 --> 00:05:30.600
that are well established, like cognitive load theory, multimedia learning theory, all

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:31.600
the rest.

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:32.600
They all apply to learning.

00:05:32.600 --> 00:05:35.760
And if we apply these to the data science training environment, we should be able to

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:38.480
make a much better workshop.

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:43.559
If there are any trainers in the audience, I strongly recommend learning about these things,

00:05:43.640 --> 00:05:47.640
and there's a book that makes it really simple to learn about the research.

00:05:47.640 --> 00:05:50.679
All the most important educational research is covered in this book here.

00:05:50.679 --> 00:05:54.200
It's called How Learning Happens by Paul Kirshner and Carl Hendrick.

00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:57.279
So that's something you might consider if you're developing your own training programs.

00:05:57.279 --> 00:06:02.600
Anyways, I took this and I put it into my workshops and my training programs, and it

00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:05.119
worked amazingly.

00:06:05.119 --> 00:06:07.239
People love the workshops that I was creating.

00:06:07.239 --> 00:06:11.760
I started to win awards like crazy.

00:06:11.959 --> 00:06:17.519
Correspondence was sent to me from the American Statistical Association because I'd come to

00:06:17.519 --> 00:06:23.040
teach at their JSM conferences, and they'd poll all the students, their statisticians,

00:06:23.040 --> 00:06:27.920
and the workshop that was highest rated amongst many, many workshops would always win an award,

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:29.640
the Excellence in Continuing Education Award.

00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:35.040
Well, I won it three years in a row, and that was unprecedented, and then because of that,

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:38.519
they hired me to go around the country and teach at different chapters, including Hawaii,

00:06:38.519 --> 00:06:40.799
so I got to go to Hawaii as a teacher.

00:06:40.839 --> 00:06:43.160
The picture of me jet lagged over their teaching.

00:06:43.160 --> 00:06:44.160
Students gave me LA.

00:06:44.160 --> 00:06:46.320
That was pretty cool.

00:06:46.320 --> 00:06:47.839
But I thought, wow, this is great.

00:06:47.839 --> 00:06:48.959
I've cracked the code.

00:06:48.959 --> 00:06:51.239
I can teach a really effective workshop.

00:06:51.239 --> 00:06:55.760
These students are telling me in every workshop that learning R is going to be life-changing

00:06:55.760 --> 00:06:59.399
for them because they could see how it would be so much easier to do the things they're

00:06:59.399 --> 00:07:01.320
doing and they'll actually be able to do some more.

00:07:01.320 --> 00:07:06.040
It'll be like a phase shift because they have the reproducibility and executability of their

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:07.040
code.

00:07:07.239 --> 00:07:14.720
So I thought, the world looks pretty good, but I still have a background in psychology

00:07:14.720 --> 00:07:19.359
and I started exploring educational psychology, the literature of psychology that's related

00:07:19.359 --> 00:07:24.160
to education, and there are some disturbing signals in there, and I'll share some of those

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:25.519
with you.

00:07:25.519 --> 00:07:31.720
For example, the best we could tell based on research is that students only remember

00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:37.559
about 56%, so about half of the content, that you tell them in a lecture.

00:07:37.559 --> 00:07:42.279
And that's if you test them immediately after the lecture.

00:07:42.279 --> 00:07:46.119
And we expect that this drops off from there as time goes by.

00:07:46.119 --> 00:07:49.239
There's the study where I'm getting this number from.

00:07:49.239 --> 00:07:52.839
But this is sometimes very disturbing if you're a trainer.

00:07:52.839 --> 00:07:56.559
Not only is this disturbing, the students who are being tested here are undergraduates

00:07:56.559 --> 00:08:00.519
at college who we might think of as professional learners.

00:08:00.519 --> 00:08:04.359
If they can only manage to remember half of what they learned in a lecture, then the

00:08:04.359 --> 00:08:08.440
distracted adult let's go right back to all their other work responsibilities, probably

00:08:08.440 --> 00:08:11.320
go learn even less.

00:08:11.320 --> 00:08:14.000
That's not very good.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:20.359
Next other studies, here's a study that looks at procedural instruction.

00:08:20.359 --> 00:08:24.399
So this is more like teaching someone how to do a procedure, whether that's using a

00:08:24.399 --> 00:08:29.880
machine or fitting a certain model or something that you do, it's a behavior.

00:08:29.880 --> 00:08:33.000
So it's not like something you take a test on later.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:36.719
And they find the same numbers immediately after the training, where the students are

00:08:36.719 --> 00:08:41.719
doing the thing, only 60% of them can reproduce it.

00:08:41.719 --> 00:08:43.840
And then six months later, that drops to 40%.

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:47.799
One year later, that drops to 30% and so on.

00:08:47.799 --> 00:08:49.919
So that's not great either.

00:08:49.919 --> 00:08:53.719
And most trainers I discovered weren't aware of this at all.

00:08:53.719 --> 00:08:59.080
But you can look at the students being trained and kind of get the sense that this is exactly

00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:02.280
what is happening.

00:09:02.280 --> 00:09:07.280
I went back to my workshops, and I continued to teach, and I continued to get rave reviews.

00:09:07.280 --> 00:09:11.520
And I realized what all the knobs were to make student satisfaction really high in a

00:09:11.520 --> 00:09:12.520
workshop.

00:09:12.520 --> 00:09:18.520
But I also realized they don't really relate to the stickiness of what the student's learning.

00:09:18.520 --> 00:09:22.320
And anecdotally, I started to check back in on some of my students, and I realized, even

00:09:22.320 --> 00:09:26.719
though they love the workshop, and they could do lots of great things in the workshop, they

00:09:26.719 --> 00:09:30.840
weren't doing those things a year later or six months later.

00:09:30.840 --> 00:09:33.479
To me, that seems like a training failure.

00:09:33.479 --> 00:09:40.000
And I'm not going to speak for everyone, but I almost feel like it's a dirty secret of

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:45.200
the training industry that you don't get terrific outcomes as a trainer.

00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:48.799
I've heard people talk about marketing and say, you know, we know half of what we do

00:09:48.799 --> 00:09:49.799
works.

00:09:49.799 --> 00:09:50.799
We just don't know which half.

00:09:50.799 --> 00:09:54.599
Well, it seems like that might be the case for training as well.

00:09:54.599 --> 00:09:58.640
But we're dealing with a field where people aren't trained to be trainers.

00:09:58.640 --> 00:10:02.000
So I think there's lots of upside to do much, much better.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:08.799
And that's what we set out to do at RStudio, which is now Posit.

00:10:08.799 --> 00:10:12.799
And the way we fix this is by looking into why this happens.

00:10:12.799 --> 00:10:15.359
So some of you may have seen this graph before.

00:10:15.359 --> 00:10:20.840
It's called the forgetting curves or the ebbing house curves based on the gentleman who first

00:10:20.840 --> 00:10:22.559
postulated it.

00:10:22.559 --> 00:10:27.440
This summarizes a body of research that goes all the way back to the 1800s, has been verified

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:29.119
in many different fields.

00:10:29.119 --> 00:10:31.799
It's just a fact of human life.

00:10:31.799 --> 00:10:37.679
The way to look at the graph is these blue lines are someone's ability to do something,

00:10:37.679 --> 00:10:43.479
be that to do a task, to remember vocabulary, to take a test.

00:10:43.479 --> 00:10:46.320
It's just their ability to do that thing that they learned.

00:10:46.320 --> 00:10:52.239
And the first blue line shows how that ability changes over time.

00:10:52.919 --> 00:10:55.440
Depending on the ability and what the training is like, it drops off at different rates.

00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:56.960
So there's no units on that axis.

00:10:56.960 --> 00:10:58.640
This is more of a model here.

00:10:58.640 --> 00:11:03.520
But what happens consistently is your ability to do something drops off after you first

00:11:03.520 --> 00:11:04.520
learn it.

00:11:04.520 --> 00:11:08.679
And especially if you never use it again, your brain basically cannibalizes the resources

00:11:08.679 --> 00:11:12.760
that devoted that ability and uses them to do other more important things.

00:11:12.760 --> 00:11:16.000
And eventually you can't do that thing anymore.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.239
But you don't have to settle for that outcome.

00:11:19.239 --> 00:11:24.320
If you wait until that thing starts to get difficult for you, and then you practice it

00:11:24.320 --> 00:11:28.080
and do it again, you're essentially relearning it through your practice.

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:31.280
And you do it again, and you jump up to the next blue line.

00:11:31.280 --> 00:11:34.719
So your ability started to fall off, but you practice, and now you can do it again pretty

00:11:34.719 --> 00:11:35.719
well.

00:11:35.719 --> 00:11:38.440
And then it starts to fall off again.

00:11:38.440 --> 00:11:42.559
But it doesn't fall off as fast as it did the first time if you had never practiced

00:11:42.559 --> 00:11:43.559
it.

00:11:43.559 --> 00:11:47.200
And if you repeat this process and you practice again, you'll be on the next blue line, and

00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:49.799
then the next blue line.

00:11:49.799 --> 00:11:53.640
Whenever you don't use something, your brain does start to lose its ability to do it.

00:11:53.640 --> 00:11:57.719
But the more you practice the thing, the more your brain decides to conserve those neural

00:11:57.719 --> 00:12:00.359
networks and retain that ability.

00:12:00.359 --> 00:12:03.640
Now if you've practiced something enough times, you've learned to ride the bike and it stays

00:12:03.640 --> 00:12:05.760
with you forever.

00:12:05.760 --> 00:12:13.599
You could sort of see why this doesn't play out in a workshop that you take for half a

00:12:13.599 --> 00:12:18.840
day or two days or what have you, and then you never really see it again.

00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:23.119
These practice sessions work because your brain is building new neural circuitry in

00:12:23.119 --> 00:12:24.119
between.

00:12:24.119 --> 00:12:27.520
That means you have to go to sleep, nighttime sleep, in between these sessions to really

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:29.599
build up a robust neural network.

00:12:29.599 --> 00:12:34.239
I have occasionally had people sleep in my workshops, but I don't think that was causing

00:12:34.239 --> 00:12:36.280
the effect we look for here.

00:12:36.280 --> 00:12:41.200
I'm also realizing I could have used these slides to explain this a little more clearly,

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:44.799
but this is what I just said, how the more you practice, the more it changes the trajectory

00:12:44.799 --> 00:12:48.679
of forgetting until eventually you don't really forget.

00:12:48.679 --> 00:12:55.039
All right, so we could see in the data that's how that works, but we also know from research

00:12:55.039 --> 00:12:57.320
and study why it happens.

00:12:57.320 --> 00:12:58.840
This is your brain.

00:12:58.840 --> 00:13:03.640
It's a collection of neurons that are joined together, and your abilities and the information

00:13:03.640 --> 00:13:08.239
you know and the memories you have are all encoded into your brain as networks between

00:13:08.239 --> 00:13:10.359
these neurons.

00:13:10.520 --> 00:13:14.440
The network is set up so when one neuron in the network fires, the other neurons fire

00:13:14.440 --> 00:13:18.520
as well, and they trigger whatever behavior needs to come together to make this experience

00:13:18.520 --> 00:13:21.520
that your brain is recreating for you.

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:26.859
We can imagine having two networks that do two separate things in our brain.

00:13:26.859 --> 00:13:31.919
One of these we use, every time we use it, those neurons fire together, and then your

00:13:31.919 --> 00:13:35.960
brain wires them together a little more strongly, because this is how the brain works.

00:13:35.960 --> 00:13:39.039
You probably heard neurons that fire together wire together.

00:13:39.039 --> 00:13:42.799
Every time you use it, that network gets stronger and stronger, whereas the one you

00:13:42.799 --> 00:13:45.080
don't use gets weaker and weaker.

00:13:45.080 --> 00:13:46.320
Your brain has important things to do.

00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:49.880
It's not going to maintain a network that doesn't do anything useful until eventually

00:13:49.880 --> 00:13:56.679
over time you'll have a very, very strong network at the thing you were doing, so strong

00:13:56.679 --> 00:13:59.400
that doing it no longer takes conscious thought.

00:13:59.400 --> 00:14:00.960
It's completely automated.

00:14:00.960 --> 00:14:04.760
When one of the neurons in the network fires due to some cue or trigger, all the rest just

00:14:04.760 --> 00:14:11.359
automatically cascade, and you juggle the ball, or fit the model, or interpret the data.

00:14:11.359 --> 00:14:15.080
Whereas that other neural network that we never use, it doesn't even exist anymore.

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:17.960
It's gone.

00:14:17.960 --> 00:14:22.280
This is the biological phenomenon that explains the forgetting curves.

00:14:22.280 --> 00:14:25.440
Like I said, this wiring together occurs while you're sleeping, so this is something that

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:32.159
happens with lots of repetition over a long period of time, weeks, let's say.

00:14:32.559 --> 00:14:37.880
If we go back to our model and think about, do we want our colleague to be able to do

00:14:37.880 --> 00:14:43.559
this new skill, pick a skill where the answer is yes, and then consider, what is going to

00:14:43.559 --> 00:14:47.919
determine whether or not he or she could do that six months from now?

00:14:47.919 --> 00:14:52.760
You'll discover it's very little to do with the initial instruction we give the colleague

00:14:52.760 --> 00:15:01.200
and everything to do with the amount of practice they've had shortly after that instruction.

00:15:01.239 --> 00:15:04.159
How do we train to take advantage of this?

00:15:04.159 --> 00:15:13.200
How do we train to make people who can use R as well as SAS six months from now?

00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:18.119
Something else to consider as well, just watching a lecture or watching a video on your computer

00:15:18.119 --> 00:15:22.679
about doing something probably builds a neural network, but it's a neural network that's

00:15:22.679 --> 00:15:25.200
related to sitting still and watching a video unfold.

00:15:25.200 --> 00:15:29.440
It's actually doing the thing that builds a neural network so you'll later use to do

00:15:29.440 --> 00:15:30.440
the thing.

00:15:30.960 --> 00:15:34.400
We have to be conscious of that in training too, and unfortunately a lot of training doesn't

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:37.159
really focus on the student actually doing the things.

00:15:37.159 --> 00:15:40.440
It's more, hey, watch this video.

00:15:40.440 --> 00:15:48.520
Maybe there's a multiple choice question afterwards, maybe there's not.

00:15:48.520 --> 00:15:49.520
What does this mean for us?

00:15:49.520 --> 00:15:53.640
Well, the revelation we had at our studio is that data science is a skill.

00:15:53.640 --> 00:15:58.520
If you want to learn to do good data science with code or otherwise, you have to practice

00:15:58.599 --> 00:16:00.599
it and learn it as a skill.

00:16:00.599 --> 00:16:05.039
A great analogy would be playing the piano or some musical instrument.

00:16:05.039 --> 00:16:06.479
Those are skills as well.

00:16:06.479 --> 00:16:14.080
There are things you need to learn like how to read notation, rhythm, music, but you also

00:16:14.080 --> 00:16:17.400
need to sit down and practice the piano if you want to play a song on the piano.

00:16:17.400 --> 00:16:25.000
You wouldn't expect to do this well by watching an online course or videos online.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:28.280
Maybe I can supplement what you are going to do to learn to play the piano.

00:16:29.039 --> 00:16:32.039
You wouldn't expect to learn to play the piano well either by attending a short workshop

00:16:32.039 --> 00:16:33.559
that lasts for a day or two days.

00:16:33.559 --> 00:16:38.159
I mean, it might help, it might get you enthusiastic to do the practice you need afterwards, but

00:16:38.159 --> 00:16:43.039
at the end of the day, if you want to play the piano, you do need to practice over time.

00:16:43.039 --> 00:16:47.880
And usually with some sort of feedback from an expert who's mentoring you as you play

00:16:47.880 --> 00:16:48.880
the piano.

00:16:48.880 --> 00:16:51.320
And the same is true for data science.

00:16:51.320 --> 00:16:55.799
We need to use practice over time to learn to do it in a new way.

00:16:55.799 --> 00:16:56.799
All right.

00:16:56.799 --> 00:16:57.799
So what about online courses?

00:16:58.320 --> 00:17:00.320
They can last over time, right?

00:17:00.320 --> 00:17:07.319
Well, what we find or what you would find too, if you research the training communities,

00:17:07.319 --> 00:17:09.760
students don't complete online courses.

00:17:09.760 --> 00:17:13.400
They don't stay very engaged with them even when they do complete them.

00:17:13.400 --> 00:17:18.079
And that being someone who's designed many online courses, I can tell you, it's very

00:17:18.079 --> 00:17:23.719
hard to design an online course that multiple students can come to and be challenged by

00:17:23.719 --> 00:17:25.839
without a teacher there overseeing the process.

00:17:25.880 --> 00:17:30.280
You sort of have to design for the lowest common denominator, and that's not enough

00:17:30.280 --> 00:17:34.040
to help the rest of the class learn.

00:17:34.040 --> 00:17:39.479
When we look at really well-supported massive online courses, like the Johns Hopkins or

00:17:39.479 --> 00:17:46.280
Coursera MOOCs, we see that it's typical for about 10% of students to finish those.

00:17:46.280 --> 00:17:51.119
I've also had the privilege in my life to look at the data for some online data science

00:17:51.119 --> 00:17:54.800
training providers because we were partnering with them, and what we saw was something that

00:17:54.800 --> 00:17:57.560
was very similar to a gym.

00:17:57.560 --> 00:18:00.680
Lots of people pay for a subscription to go to the gym, but at the end of the day, they

00:18:00.680 --> 00:18:02.239
never show up and go to the gym.

00:18:02.239 --> 00:18:04.040
They're just sort of paying.

00:18:04.040 --> 00:18:09.920
It's great if you're a gym and you're collecting money, but it's not great if you're paying

00:18:09.920 --> 00:18:15.599
to get student outcomes because if the students don't go there and engage, they don't change.

00:18:15.599 --> 00:18:20.319
And the missing element for these online courses, whether it's a MOOC or this gym model, is

00:18:20.319 --> 00:18:22.000
motivation.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:25.920
So lots of people think education works this way.

00:18:25.920 --> 00:18:26.920
There's an educator.

00:18:26.920 --> 00:18:28.560
They have the information that the student needs.

00:18:28.560 --> 00:18:29.560
There's a student.

00:18:29.560 --> 00:18:39.459
We just need to transfer that information over, and then the student's now an expert.

00:18:39.459 --> 00:18:42.680
But that's not how education works at all.

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:45.920
Information is cheap and easy, and you could get it from the library or YouTube or wherever

00:18:45.920 --> 00:18:50.520
you want it, but if you want to learn to use that information, you have to do something

00:18:50.520 --> 00:18:55.359
after you acquire it, and this is the hardest part of learning something.

00:18:55.359 --> 00:19:00.400
You have to practice it in a loop over and over again, and it's easy to start practicing

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:03.640
things the wrong way, and as a student, you might not even know you're doing it, and then

00:19:03.640 --> 00:19:06.160
you're just building neural networks that encode mistakes.

00:19:06.160 --> 00:19:08.160
It's not going to work out well.

00:19:08.160 --> 00:19:13.239
You need to practice and get feedback, maybe some coaching.

00:19:13.239 --> 00:19:21.359
Practice itself is hard work, and all of that work requires you to be motivated.

00:19:21.359 --> 00:19:26.839
It's hard for busy adults to stay motivated at one more form of busyness, but this blue

00:19:26.839 --> 00:19:33.359
loop here is what matters if we want our colleagues to become excellent R users or Python users

00:19:33.359 --> 00:19:35.719
or data scientists.

00:19:35.719 --> 00:19:37.920
Most training environments ignore the blue loop.

00:19:37.920 --> 00:19:40.439
It happens after the training's over.

00:19:40.439 --> 00:19:45.119
So what we decided to do is focus on that blue loop to make it easy to do the hard work

00:19:45.119 --> 00:19:49.239
of learning, to do it as efficiently as possible so you know it's paying off, and to give you

00:19:49.239 --> 00:19:52.640
the coaching that keeps that practice loop where it should be so you're practicing the

00:19:52.640 --> 00:19:55.000
right things instead of spinning off into mistakes.

00:19:55.000 --> 00:19:57.880
So what does that look like?

00:19:57.880 --> 00:20:00.599
How do humans actually learn skills?

00:20:00.599 --> 00:20:05.800
Might seem like the training industry is botched, and if you want to help your people transition

00:20:05.800 --> 00:20:10.739
over to R, you have a hard time of it, but it's not actually the case.

00:20:10.739 --> 00:20:15.239
We learn skills every day in modalities that are very familiar and that lots of people

00:20:15.239 --> 00:20:16.560
have confidence in.

00:20:16.560 --> 00:20:18.800
So we use pianos as a metaphor earlier.

00:20:18.800 --> 00:20:23.959
If you wanted to learn to play the piano, you would find a piano coach or music teacher

00:20:23.959 --> 00:20:28.119
and they'd give you some one-on-one feedback, and it'd be a process.

00:20:28.119 --> 00:20:33.060
But every apprenticeship also works this way, every internship, every residency.

00:20:33.060 --> 00:20:36.979
If the thing you're trying to learn happens to be a physical skill, we call it coaching.

00:20:36.979 --> 00:20:39.819
These things work all the time.

00:20:39.819 --> 00:20:46.020
We need an experience like this for using R, for doing data science.

00:20:46.020 --> 00:20:51.660
So how should your analysts learn data science or code or R or Python?

00:20:51.660 --> 00:20:54.579
We've put together an experience that looks like this, and this is my answer.

00:20:54.579 --> 00:20:56.380
This is how it should look.

00:20:56.380 --> 00:21:02.260
If you train with Posit Academy, the first thing you have is a mentor.

00:21:02.459 --> 00:21:07.140
A mentor is someone who knows how to do data science with R, and they're going to help

00:21:07.140 --> 00:21:08.140
you.

00:21:08.140 --> 00:21:09.780
They're going to coach you to learn it.

00:21:09.780 --> 00:21:12.780
We have two types of mentor at Academy.

00:21:12.780 --> 00:21:13.780
One is the type that we provide.

00:21:13.780 --> 00:21:18.739
We provide experts to help people learn, and the other type is a mentor that the company

00:21:18.739 --> 00:21:20.900
who engages us provides.

00:21:20.900 --> 00:21:24.420
They act as an apprentice in the course experience, an apprentice mentor.

00:21:24.420 --> 00:21:28.380
But they're another resource for students, and the cool thing about apprentice mentors

00:21:28.459 --> 00:21:33.140
from the company is after the experience is over, that apprentice is still at the company,

00:21:33.140 --> 00:21:38.540
still acting as a mentor, still forming the node of a support network within the company,

00:21:38.540 --> 00:21:40.140
so you build up a community of practice.

00:21:40.140 --> 00:21:43.459
I might talk more about that in a minute.

00:21:43.459 --> 00:21:47.979
The next thing you have in addition to your mentor is group mates.

00:21:47.979 --> 00:21:51.060
We've designed a cohort-based learning experience where no one learns in isolation.

00:21:51.060 --> 00:21:55.979
They learn in small groups of five to seven students who are all trying to learn the same

00:21:55.979 --> 00:21:57.800
thing as you are.

00:21:57.800 --> 00:22:02.359
So as you go through the course, not only do you have an expert who has your back, who's

00:22:02.359 --> 00:22:07.119
coaching you, you also have fellow travelers who you could discuss things with.

00:22:07.119 --> 00:22:11.640
You could work through problems together, and you may not even realize it, but you can

00:22:11.640 --> 00:22:19.000
hold each other accountable and motivated as you go through the process.

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:20.839
So those are the people involved.

00:22:20.839 --> 00:22:23.000
Next we give you a project to do.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:26.000
So an Academy course is not a course.

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:27.000
It's an apprenticeship.

00:22:27.199 --> 00:22:31.719
You're going to do something very real and very close to what you do at your job because

00:22:31.719 --> 00:22:34.199
that's ultimately what you want to learn how to do.

00:22:34.199 --> 00:22:38.000
We want you to see the value of everything you're learning, and the best way to do that

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:42.920
is to make it similar to your work, which is very valuable to you.

00:22:42.920 --> 00:22:48.119
So an example project would be comparing different treatments, maybe with asthma, maybe with

00:22:48.119 --> 00:22:50.199
some sort of disease.

00:22:50.199 --> 00:22:53.079
If you came to us from finance, we'd give you a finance project and whatnot, but we

00:22:53.319 --> 00:22:58.040
give you something that is close to what you're going to do, and you're going to do it under

00:22:58.040 --> 00:23:02.560
the guidance of the mentor and with the support of your group mates.

00:23:02.560 --> 00:23:06.560
Each project is scoped to cover what we think or we have found over the past decade is essential

00:23:06.560 --> 00:23:14.280
to learning R. So that begins with importing data, exploring the data with plots and visualizations,

00:23:14.280 --> 00:23:17.280
wrangling your data, analyzing it.

00:23:17.280 --> 00:23:22.280
If you're familiar with R, I'm talking about dplyr, tidyr, joins, that sort of thing, but

00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:26.000
also fitting models to your data.

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:30.280
And then how do you summarize your work to communicate with someone else, and how do

00:23:30.280 --> 00:23:35.560
you do that reproducibly so the next time you have a similar project, you're already

00:23:35.560 --> 00:23:40.400
way ahead and you start with your previous work versus making it up from scratch.

00:23:40.400 --> 00:23:47.119
We focus on R Markdown and now increasingly Cordo, which is the next version of R Markdown.

00:23:47.119 --> 00:23:51.760
So you're going to do all of that to complete your project and do that real life thing that

00:23:51.760 --> 00:23:55.920
you will presumably now be able to do at your job and create a lot of value with.

00:23:55.920 --> 00:23:57.319
But how do we make that happen?

00:23:57.319 --> 00:24:00.040
It can't happen out of thin air.

00:24:00.040 --> 00:24:03.319
We break the project into 10 progressive milestones.

00:24:03.319 --> 00:24:05.160
Each week you work on one of these milestones.

00:24:05.160 --> 00:24:09.800
When you get to the 10th one, you finish the project, you have your portfolio piece, which

00:24:09.800 --> 00:24:15.160
is a report that shows the conclusion of all your data science work.

00:24:15.160 --> 00:24:17.640
But each of those milestones build up to that in sequence.

00:24:17.640 --> 00:24:22.199
So first you learn the basics of working with R, how to troubleshoot, what to do if

00:24:22.199 --> 00:24:26.359
you get stuck and you need help, or what to do if you hear of a new package or a new function

00:24:26.359 --> 00:24:28.680
and you want to teach yourself how to use it.

00:24:28.680 --> 00:24:30.160
We teach you how to teach yourself.

00:24:30.160 --> 00:24:34.760
That's a big part of working with R. Then you learn visualization, then you learn data

00:24:34.760 --> 00:24:38.920
wrinkling and joints, and so on.

00:24:38.920 --> 00:24:45.199
Think of the project as the skeleton or the backbone of the course.

00:24:45.199 --> 00:24:49.239
Most courses have a syllabus, but we have a project, and it functions a little bit like

00:24:49.239 --> 00:24:50.239
a syllabus.

00:24:50.239 --> 00:24:54.239
You're going to need to do all these real-life things to finish the project.

00:24:54.239 --> 00:25:00.280
We divide into our milestones, and then we prepare tutorials that teach you what you

00:25:00.280 --> 00:25:02.599
need to do to do that milestone.

00:25:02.599 --> 00:25:07.479
So if you have to fit a model in R and you're just learning R, you don't know how to do

00:25:07.479 --> 00:25:08.479
that.

00:25:08.479 --> 00:25:11.079
We're going to assign you tutorials from the library tutorials we've written that will

00:25:11.079 --> 00:25:14.880
show you how to fit models in R. These tutorials are designed to teach through

00:25:15.560 --> 00:25:16.560
exercises.

00:25:16.560 --> 00:25:20.199
We've written grading code to give us a type of artificial intelligence that will look

00:25:20.199 --> 00:25:24.439
at the code you submit, and if it's wrong, they'll give you advice on how to fix that

00:25:24.439 --> 00:25:25.439
code.

00:25:25.439 --> 00:25:30.119
It doesn't focus on unit tests or making sure your result is right, it looks at what you're

00:25:30.119 --> 00:25:35.560
writing and tells you how to change that, because that's what you need to learn.

00:25:35.560 --> 00:25:41.160
And then at the end of that week, after you've learned your tutorials, done your milestone,

00:25:41.199 --> 00:25:46.040
we have you get together with your group and present what you've done.

00:25:46.040 --> 00:25:50.800
We ask you for each milestone to recreate something, a step in your project.

00:25:50.800 --> 00:25:54.280
If you've studied the tutorials, you should be able to do that recreation.

00:25:54.280 --> 00:25:59.640
But then we ask you to teach yourself something new to create a personalized or extended milestone

00:25:59.640 --> 00:26:02.239
that you could present to your groupmates.

00:26:02.239 --> 00:26:05.119
This creates a lot of cross-pollination when the groupmates get together, they learn from

00:26:05.119 --> 00:26:10.839
each other, but it also helps you practice teaching yourself new parts of an ever-expanding

00:26:10.839 --> 00:26:16.160
free and open-source language like R.

00:26:16.160 --> 00:26:22.400
The group sessions, we hold them over Zoom or Microsoft Teams, looks something like this.

00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:26.000
So some of our former illustrious clients.

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:30.920
You share your screen, you're going to be working with the RStudio IDE, which is a real

00:26:30.920 --> 00:26:33.640
tool many day scientists use.

00:26:33.640 --> 00:26:37.479
What's in Posit Workbench, you also end up working with Posit Connect, so you learn how

00:26:37.479 --> 00:26:41.680
to use the real tools that you can start using the day after academy ends.

00:26:41.680 --> 00:26:45.239
In fact, most students start using them well before academy ends at their work to create

00:26:45.239 --> 00:26:49.199
value.

00:26:49.199 --> 00:26:52.359
Your groupmates give you the accountability.

00:26:52.359 --> 00:26:55.439
You have to show up with something to show them.

00:26:55.439 --> 00:26:59.079
You also meet with them during the week one time for a co-working session to work through

00:26:59.079 --> 00:27:01.079
trouble together.

00:27:01.079 --> 00:27:04.680
But they're more than just the people who make sure you did your assignment.

00:27:04.680 --> 00:27:07.560
After the course is over, they're your future support network.

00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:12.079
They're the beginnings of a community of practice that you've established by learning R inside

00:27:12.079 --> 00:27:16.800
your pharmaceutical company.

00:27:16.800 --> 00:27:21.640
So a typical week, do some tutorials, complete and personalize a milestone, present to the

00:27:21.640 --> 00:27:22.640
group.

00:27:22.640 --> 00:27:25.920
In between, you have a co-working session with your groupmates to help out.

00:27:25.920 --> 00:27:29.760
It's optional, but we strongly encourage people to go, and most people do go.

00:27:29.760 --> 00:27:33.319
And then you have the communication channel like Slack or Microsoft Teams where you can

00:27:33.319 --> 00:27:36.400
discuss the project and answer each other's questions.

00:27:36.400 --> 00:27:38.400
And your mentors are there too to answer questions.

00:27:38.400 --> 00:27:42.479
Your mentors also have each of the in-person sessions.

00:27:42.479 --> 00:27:47.160
Repeat this until you finish your project, and that's what the academy experience looks

00:27:47.160 --> 00:27:48.319
like.

00:27:48.319 --> 00:27:49.680
So does this work?

00:27:49.680 --> 00:27:54.760
Can this teach someone who doesn't know R to use R and do real data science with it?

00:27:54.760 --> 00:27:56.880
The answer is yes.

00:27:56.880 --> 00:27:59.359
We've taught about 600 students so far using this method.

00:27:59.359 --> 00:28:02.359
We have about a 95% completion rate.

00:28:02.400 --> 00:28:06.400
This is for a course that lasts 10 weeks, 12 weeks normally, because we put in some

00:28:06.400 --> 00:28:10.640
breaks for holidays and stuff just based on how the year works out, and the students stick

00:28:10.640 --> 00:28:11.640
with it.

00:28:11.640 --> 00:28:18.040
Here's an example student, Keith Wickle from Kellogg Company.

00:28:18.040 --> 00:28:22.199
I'm calling him out as an example because he posted on LinkedIn in public.

00:28:22.199 --> 00:28:26.880
But what we see with other students is similar to what we see with Keith.

00:28:26.880 --> 00:28:30.680
People are really excited to be students in this sort of experience.

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:35.680
They're really excited to actually apprentice on something, learn it well, and have a mentor

00:28:35.680 --> 00:28:40.119
there to help them through any question that comes up, any challenge that they have, or

00:28:40.119 --> 00:28:43.520
anything they want to explore that we didn't put in the course, but they know they're interested

00:28:43.520 --> 00:28:44.520
in.

00:28:44.520 --> 00:28:48.079
They can do it and discuss it with their mentor and group mates.

00:28:48.079 --> 00:28:52.760
So our students like it, but our customers are actually companies.

00:28:52.760 --> 00:28:58.000
We're trying to help companies create capacity to do work that didn't exist previously in

00:28:58.000 --> 00:28:59.000
their company.

00:28:59.319 --> 00:29:01.479
And it works there, too.

00:29:01.479 --> 00:29:05.599
This is probably the most on-the-nose quote from a previous customer.

