As the milestones get more complicated, they sort of become more divergent.

00:34:12.679 --> 00:34:20.080
So in the second week already, you'll be making plots and each project is guided by a motivating

00:34:20.080 --> 00:34:23.560
question, which might be as simple as, you know, is there a difference between these

00:34:23.560 --> 00:34:25.159
two treatments?

00:34:25.159 --> 00:34:30.239
Or it might be, you know, what factors predict this thing?

00:34:30.239 --> 00:34:35.159
And normally within those questions, there's multiple relationships you might search for

00:34:35.159 --> 00:34:39.719
or discover, especially if it's what factors cause this, who knows?

00:34:39.719 --> 00:34:47.280
So we encourage the students to be curious, explore as many relationships and data, maybe

00:34:47.280 --> 00:34:51.760
even make their own new variables or features to explore and visualize with different types

00:34:51.760 --> 00:34:52.760
of plots.

00:34:52.760 --> 00:34:57.360
Even when you're comparing treatment groups, you might want to look for differences beyond,

00:34:57.360 --> 00:34:59.560
you know, the outcome of that disease.

00:34:59.560 --> 00:35:03.760
There might be meaningful differences in like blood pressure or things that we'd want to

00:35:03.760 --> 00:35:04.760
know about.

00:35:05.360 --> 00:35:12.199
So I would say as soon as the second week, there's lots of room for experimentation,

00:35:12.199 --> 00:35:15.159
exploration, reporting new things back.

00:35:15.159 --> 00:35:21.760
Also that extension piece allows people to really learn a lot of different things.

