So we have many projects that already exist and we've developed a consultation with clients

00:37:29.439 --> 00:37:30.439
and whatnot.

00:37:30.439 --> 00:37:36.719
And one of them is, no, actually that's the wrong one, but you had a specific one and

00:37:36.719 --> 00:37:37.719
that was-

00:37:37.719 --> 00:37:41.639
I thought because it's focusing more on clinical, there, right there.

00:37:41.639 --> 00:37:42.639
Yeah.

00:37:42.639 --> 00:37:44.760
Modification of diet and renal disease.

00:37:44.760 --> 00:37:50.719
So this, sometimes we have to be clever about getting around HIPAA and regulations and stuff.

00:37:50.719 --> 00:37:53.639
So this is data that's actually been published in scientific literature.

00:37:53.639 --> 00:37:57.479
So it's not going to trouble for using it.

00:37:57.479 --> 00:38:04.040
And it is a clinical trial that looked at four different treatment groups on renal disease,

00:38:04.040 --> 00:38:10.320
so kidney disease, and the treatment groups varied the level of blood pressure medication

00:38:10.320 --> 00:38:13.320
the patients took and also the amount of protein in their diet.

00:38:13.320 --> 00:38:22.479
So we had four different groups and ultimately we run an ANOVA to determine whether or not

00:38:22.479 --> 00:38:25.679
there's a difference between the groups.

00:38:25.679 --> 00:38:27.719
These are the 10 milestones in the project.

00:38:27.719 --> 00:38:33.760
So first they're going to create a histogram of the measure that we're interested in, how

00:38:33.760 --> 00:38:38.719
much your kidneys can filter, the measure of kidney health.

00:38:38.719 --> 00:38:41.879
We progressively get them from using Basar.

00:38:41.879 --> 00:38:44.120
So first we just want to make sure they could use our functions.

00:38:44.120 --> 00:38:48.239
Then we start teaching packages like ggplot2, that's the graphics package in R.

00:38:48.239 --> 00:38:52.639
And they group and summarize by patient to reveal things that you wouldn't find in the

00:38:52.639 --> 00:38:56.239
data as it is, but you can derive from the data.

00:38:56.239 --> 00:38:59.719
We join in a second data set that they can work with.

00:38:59.719 --> 00:39:04.120
We tidy and pivot tables.

00:39:04.120 --> 00:39:11.040
We start reporting our results in a way that makes it useful to turn in assignments, but

00:39:11.040 --> 00:39:18.360
also to turn in reports or decisions to people that your team is working for.

00:39:18.360 --> 00:39:24.520
We work with different types of data such as strings, dates, times, depends on what

00:39:24.520 --> 00:39:27.719
sort of data you would work with at work.

00:39:27.719 --> 00:39:30.360
That's what you'll work on on your project, but we do teach you how to work with each

00:39:30.360 --> 00:39:33.520
type of data in the tutorials.

