00:41:09.719 --> 00:41:14.639
But one was, can you share more details on how Academy was structured for customers in

00:41:14.639 --> 00:41:15.639
life sciences?

00:41:15.639 --> 00:41:22.439
Or are there any measures of student engagement and overall success in life science?

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:24.000
Yes.

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:32.120
So, first of all, Academy is not structured specifically for life sciences.

00:41:32.120 --> 00:41:41.159
It's structured specifically for people who need to learn R or Python to do what they

00:41:41.159 --> 00:41:43.800
do.

00:41:43.800 --> 00:41:47.959
We've become experts in teaching R and Python.

00:41:48.040 --> 00:41:53.000
And what we found is it's not very different whether you need to use R to do this or to

00:41:53.000 --> 00:41:54.000
do that.

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:57.600
It's not even that different if you're coming from SAS or Excel.

00:41:57.600 --> 00:42:03.479
If you're coming from SAS, we can use the knowledge you have about SAS as a springboard

00:42:03.479 --> 00:42:09.479
to connect to R. But at the end of the day, we're not going to give you a translation

00:42:09.479 --> 00:42:14.479
guide that shows you how to ask where the bathroom is in R. We want to teach you to

00:42:14.479 --> 00:42:19.760
teach, to speak fluently in R, and that's what we achieved in 10 weeks.

00:42:19.760 --> 00:42:25.360
So our structure looks the same for life sciences as for other industries.

00:42:25.360 --> 00:42:30.899
You need to know how the mental models of the R language, so it's divided into functions

00:42:30.899 --> 00:42:32.959
and objects, and this is what those mean.

00:42:32.959 --> 00:42:37.760
You need to know where to get your help from, whether or not you're going to use clinical

00:42:37.760 --> 00:42:42.639
trials data or preclinical trials data, the R language operates the same way.

00:42:42.639 --> 00:42:45.120
You need to know the tools that execute your code.

00:42:45.120 --> 00:42:49.600
You need to know procedures for backing out of something that didn't work and finding

00:42:49.600 --> 00:42:52.320
the right path forward.

00:42:52.320 --> 00:42:56.879
Then there's a lot with data that is also remarkably similar across different fields.

00:42:56.879 --> 00:43:00.600
So we make sure you know how to get your data into R where you could use it.

00:43:00.600 --> 00:43:04.760
If you have really big data, we'll teach you how to get R to the data in the database using

00:43:04.760 --> 00:43:06.560
the dbplyr package.

00:43:06.560 --> 00:43:11.360
If once you have your data, you need to know how to join tables together, R works best

00:43:11.360 --> 00:43:14.919
when you put everything in one table before you analyze it, we teach you that, and that's

00:43:14.919 --> 00:43:17.080
field independent.

00:43:17.080 --> 00:43:21.959
Tidying your data, R works best if your data is in rectangular format or tidy data format,

00:43:21.959 --> 00:43:23.479
we teach you that.

00:43:23.479 --> 00:43:25.000
How you make a plot is the same.

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:32.639
There's so many commonalities across the industries that really, there's just one and a half or

00:43:32.639 --> 00:43:37.600
so weeks that are different from task to task at this level, and that's what the projects

00:43:37.600 --> 00:43:38.600
capture.

00:43:38.600 --> 00:43:40.620
So perhaps that's what I should be talking towards.

00:43:40.620 --> 00:43:43.899
Each project teaches the scope of all those things.

00:43:43.899 --> 00:43:48.219
It's the scope of what you'd find inside the book R for data science, by the way.

00:43:48.219 --> 00:43:52.620
But it takes the payoff step, what I call the payoff step, the model that's valuable

00:43:52.620 --> 00:43:57.620
to you with the type of data you use, and the tweaks that are idiosyncratic to the type

00:43:57.620 --> 00:44:01.500
of data you use, and it matches those to your industry.

00:44:01.500 --> 00:44:04.139
So how do we structure things for life sciences?

00:44:04.139 --> 00:44:08.540
We made projects that looked at data that life scientists or life science industries

00:44:08.540 --> 00:44:14.219
use, and that asked questions and answered the questions that life scientists ask an

00:44:14.219 --> 00:44:16.300
answer of that data.

00:44:16.300 --> 00:44:20.860
We don't train anyone to be a life scientist, we train them to be a life scientist who uses

00:44:20.860 --> 00:44:24.500
R, but we assume we're meeting them as life scientists already.

00:44:24.500 --> 00:44:31.100
Now we just show what, how to use R to do the things that they're interested in.

00:44:31.100 --> 00:44:32.699
Thank you so much, Garrett.

00:44:32.699 --> 00:44:37.699
And I know we had Devin backstage kind of helping with some of the questions in the

00:44:37.699 --> 00:44:38.699
chat too.

00:44:38.699 --> 00:44:42.979
So I wanted to pull you on here as well, Devin, because I know you work with so closely with

00:44:42.979 --> 00:44:46.979
many of our life sciences, life science customers as well.

00:44:46.979 --> 00:44:50.540
I just want to see if you had anything to add to that too.

00:44:50.540 --> 00:44:52.060
Yeah, thanks, Rachel.

