Can everyone hear me okay?

00:44:53.939 --> 00:44:56.620
Yeah, you sound great.

00:44:56.620 --> 00:44:57.820
Awesome.

00:44:57.820 --> 00:45:03.260
I think part of the flavor that I can add that Garrett really hit home throughout the

00:45:03.260 --> 00:45:11.459
entire webinar is that to frame Academy against some of the leading questions that you'll

00:45:11.459 --> 00:45:18.139
often see is that groups are coming with very differentiated needs, you know, even in very

00:45:18.139 --> 00:45:21.020
specific areas like just clinical programming, right?

00:45:21.020 --> 00:45:25.979
For some groups, we have this large set of SAS programmers, and we're trying to convert

00:45:25.979 --> 00:45:31.260
them to R. For other groups, they're trying to do novel analytics that they've never done

00:45:31.260 --> 00:45:32.260
before.

00:45:32.260 --> 00:45:34.540
So they're coming from like a clean slate.

00:45:34.540 --> 00:45:42.300
But ultimately, a lot of the patterns across companies across groups are still consistent.

00:45:42.300 --> 00:45:49.419
And so part of the beauty of Academy is bridging a lot of the pedagogical techniques, but recognizing

00:45:49.419 --> 00:45:55.139
the fact that the more domain specific they become, the more they're going to immediately

00:45:55.139 --> 00:45:56.340
resonate.

00:45:56.340 --> 00:46:01.340
And so I think, you know, with respect to like the analyzing clinical trial data elements,

00:46:01.340 --> 00:46:07.300
this is absolutely a call to say that, you know, we have been engaging with companies

00:46:07.300 --> 00:46:15.939
interested to do that, looking to develop a program that fits what type of work that

00:46:15.939 --> 00:46:17.659
they are trying to do.

00:46:17.659 --> 00:46:24.060
But it is a conversation to have, it is not a kind of a routine, hey, everyone is going

00:46:24.060 --> 00:46:27.820
to go through these same motions, and hopefully they'll come with the same outcome.

00:46:27.820 --> 00:46:31.139
Instead, it really is about saying, what is your group trying to do?

00:46:31.139 --> 00:46:36.419
We understand and we can speak towards some of the high level objectives that most groups

00:46:36.419 --> 00:46:40.179
are coming in with, we know you're going to need to generate certain types of tables and

00:46:40.179 --> 00:46:45.939
figures and legends, or expect to do particular types of analyses.

00:46:45.939 --> 00:46:51.620
But ultimately, trying to teach that highly specifically is still not going to position

00:46:51.620 --> 00:46:57.580
a group to be able to take the learnings from Academy and extend it to all the scenarios

00:46:57.580 --> 00:46:58.580
they want.

00:46:58.580 --> 00:47:07.260
So just infused throughout the entire program, is that desire to both empower people to like,

00:47:07.260 --> 00:47:12.179
think in terms of how they're trying to approach their analytics, and give a lot of those pedagogical

00:47:12.179 --> 00:47:20.300
techniques like repetition to make sure that you're able to successfully on ramp to the

00:47:20.300 --> 00:47:21.300
language.

00:47:21.979 --> 00:47:25.659
And that's one of the observations that in kind of my last decade or so of interacting

00:47:25.659 --> 00:47:30.620
with groups is, even if they crack open a book, or they crack, crack open some courses,

00:47:30.620 --> 00:47:35.899
when they start to work on their own projects that they can't, you know, copy and paste

00:47:35.899 --> 00:47:40.780
some code snippet to work off of, it's easy to get frozen as soon as something doesn't

00:47:40.780 --> 00:47:41.780
work.

00:47:41.780 --> 00:47:43.780
And you don't really know where to go.

00:47:43.780 --> 00:47:47.939
And groups that go through Academy, we see things like they're enabled and empowered

00:47:47.939 --> 00:47:54.260
to be able to troubleshoot to diagnose and to kind of move off of the path that was covered,

00:47:54.260 --> 00:47:56.780
even within the given context.

00:47:56.780 --> 00:48:05.939
And so that's why we really look forward to being able to continue to extend those teaching

00:48:05.939 --> 00:48:13.979
engagements and really are looking for people to broach what are they interested to learn.

00:48:14.020 --> 00:48:20.260
And the answer in most cases is not going to be like, no, we won't teach that is a conversation

00:48:20.260 --> 00:48:25.419
about how are you trying to, to empower the group and what.

00:48:25.419 --> 00:48:29.060
So I think there are some of the questions of like, you know, will you teach a, you know,

00:48:29.060 --> 00:48:34.620
doing cohorts analysis or certain regression like that is, those are the questions that

00:48:34.620 --> 00:48:39.260
we're looking to start that dialogue with as part of this webinar and into the future.

00:48:39.260 --> 00:48:45.139
And so I don't know if there are any that would bubble up at the moment, but if not,

00:48:45.139 --> 00:48:51.100
I think that's the kind of question that we're looking to engage with groups to learn more

00:48:51.100 --> 00:48:55.060
about their specific needs and figure out how to make them successful.

00:48:55.060 --> 00:48:59.060
Thank you, Devin.

