So I wanted to make sure I shared on the screen here that you can access the slides

00:49:13.300 --> 00:49:18.060
at this short link, we can reshare that in the chat as well.

00:49:18.060 --> 00:49:23.139
But with that question asked, I was just curious for people that are joining us here today,

00:49:23.139 --> 00:49:29.139
are you kind of in charge of training some of the new users across your team or are you

00:49:29.139 --> 00:49:34.820
part of a data science community within your company as well?

00:49:34.820 --> 00:49:41.139
If you want to put into the chat, I'd just love to learn from you all there too.

00:49:41.139 --> 00:49:46.899
But an Academy specific question that I see from YouTube, Garrett, is how are the groupmates

00:49:46.899 --> 00:49:47.899
paired?

00:49:47.899 --> 00:49:52.219
Are they assembled by similar levels?

00:49:52.219 --> 00:49:58.179
We've experimented with this and what we do right now is we pair groupmates based on similar

00:49:58.179 --> 00:50:03.419
objectives, like the tasks to be done, they go do similar tasks.

00:50:04.219 --> 00:50:08.219
What that means is you could have some really advanced R users who may have been using R

00:50:08.219 --> 00:50:13.260
quite a bit, but not really the tidyverse or maybe not for the tasks to go do with brand

00:50:13.260 --> 00:50:14.780
new beginners.

00:50:14.780 --> 00:50:16.300
And that works quite well.

00:50:16.300 --> 00:50:19.860
Having them in the same works as well too, they both work well.

00:50:19.860 --> 00:50:24.020
But what's interesting is when you have people from different levels, the ones who are more

00:50:24.020 --> 00:50:27.379
experienced act as sort of mentors because you're putting them together in this team

00:50:27.379 --> 00:50:29.020
group experience.

00:50:29.020 --> 00:50:33.060
And any teacher will tell you that's a more effective way to learn than learning.

00:50:33.699 --> 00:50:36.780
And teaching is a great way to learn and they're there and they're teaching.

00:50:36.780 --> 00:50:43.739
And since the recreations are, we feel they're doable for beginning students, no one feels

00:50:43.739 --> 00:50:48.500
like they fall far behind, but the extensions, they can run as far and as fast as they want

00:50:48.500 --> 00:50:49.500
to.

00:50:49.500 --> 00:50:53.860
So those who are ready for more of a challenge can push themselves.

00:50:53.860 --> 00:50:57.260
The mentors are there to help them no matter what stage they start to get bogged down.

00:50:57.260 --> 00:51:00.820
And those who are beginners, well, they push themselves too.

00:51:00.979 --> 00:51:05.459
It just so happens to get bogged down here, but the mentor is there to help them too.

00:51:05.459 --> 00:51:07.500
We've had a lot of success mixing models.

00:51:07.500 --> 00:51:08.500
Thank you.

00:51:08.500 --> 00:51:18.739
One other flavor that I can add as well, that again, is another observation from interacting

00:51:18.739 --> 00:51:25.139
with a lot of these groups, both within Academy, not with Academy, doing workshops, is that

00:51:25.139 --> 00:51:32.659
there's often a perception from a lot of folks in the pharma sphere that the data science

00:51:32.659 --> 00:51:35.780
activities are like a small component of their job.

00:51:35.780 --> 00:51:43.340
Maybe they need to also be considering around how decision-making is performed, other more

00:51:43.340 --> 00:51:48.560
domain-specific activities, but ultimately a lot of their day-to-day is still spent in

00:51:48.560 --> 00:51:51.060
R doing work.

00:51:51.540 --> 00:51:57.659
Even if you have been exposed to R for a while, and you might be an intermediate even pushing

00:51:57.659 --> 00:52:07.699
into advanced, there's still a lot of value in reestablishing those fundamentals in a

00:52:07.699 --> 00:52:14.340
way that you probably had to learn on the fly on the job, where some of the activities

00:52:14.340 --> 00:52:18.540
that you used to say like, well, I know the motions to fix this.

00:52:18.540 --> 00:52:23.739
I don't exactly know why, but I wave my hands for a bit, and then eventually it works.

00:52:23.739 --> 00:52:30.100
All of a sudden, a lot of those concepts suddenly become clear and become emphasized and covered

00:52:30.100 --> 00:52:32.060
over and over.

00:52:32.060 --> 00:52:36.899
We do see, even with those intermediate users going in, even though the content itself is

00:52:36.899 --> 00:52:41.699
something that they can approach, they really are able to take off and be much more efficient

00:52:41.699 --> 00:52:45.060
with their time, especially if they're coming in and out, where they might have to set aside

00:52:45.060 --> 00:52:51.620
R for a bit to do other business activities, and they come back where those routine memorized

00:52:51.620 --> 00:52:58.100
motions easily fall away, but as you establish those foundational mental models, they stick

00:52:58.100 --> 00:53:01.020
for a lot longer.

00:53:01.020 --> 00:53:06.139
If you are that intermediate user thinking, is Academy, how would I use this?

00:53:06.139 --> 00:53:10.860
There is something to be said for those intermediate or those power users where you bridge those

00:53:10.860 --> 00:53:16.060
fundamentals in, and you can even use that to help train people within your organization

00:53:16.060 --> 00:53:23.060
as you yourself sharpen your mental models, it makes you a more effective mentor and enabler

00:53:23.060 --> 00:53:25.139
throughout your organization.

00:53:25.139 --> 00:53:28.219
Thank you.

00:53:28.219 --> 00:53:35.580
I'm noticing there are a lot of anonymous questions over on Slido, and one of them was,

00:53:35.580 --> 00:53:41.340
do you do, or can you do a Shiny course?

00:53:41.340 --> 00:53:45.659
Thank you for whoever asked that, I hope it wasn't my boss.

00:53:45.659 --> 00:53:50.739
We are developing a Shiny course, it's still in production, but it's not ready yet.

00:53:50.739 --> 00:53:55.260
It will be soon, maybe by the end of the year.

00:53:55.260 --> 00:54:01.580
Sounds great, and then we touched upon this a little bit in talking about different customers

00:54:01.580 --> 00:54:09.620
we worked with, but how specific can projects get?

00:54:09.620 --> 00:54:14.300
The projects are all very similar in that there's a dataset, you're going to visualize

00:54:14.300 --> 00:54:17.179
it, you're going to wrangle it, you're going to report on it, you're going to fit a model

00:54:17.179 --> 00:54:19.620
to it.

00:54:19.620 --> 00:54:24.060
What's in the dataset can be anything, it's up to you.

00:54:24.060 --> 00:54:30.739
As long as it has several variables, and it's nice if one's continuous and maybe one's discrete

00:54:30.739 --> 00:54:35.979
and maybe there's a binary variable, but I think you have a sense of what a rich dataset

00:54:35.979 --> 00:54:41.780
would look like, and then if the modeling method that you want to apply to it, maybe

00:54:41.780 --> 00:54:45.620
this is really what matters to whoever asked the question, if it's something that you would

00:54:45.620 --> 00:54:51.500
cover in a Stats 101 course or even a 201 course, we can go ahead and teach that right

00:54:51.500 --> 00:54:52.820
now.

00:54:52.820 --> 00:54:56.540
We will eventually be developing a course based on tidy models and machine learning

00:54:56.540 --> 00:55:01.979
where we can go much deeper, but for the course we offer today, we don't teach the

00:55:01.979 --> 00:55:06.979
statistics or the machine learning, unless it's something, some low-hanging fruit like

00:55:06.979 --> 00:55:09.899
a Stats 101 or 201 course.

00:55:09.899 --> 00:55:16.780
So time series, sure, survival analysis, yeah, linear models, ANOVA, logistic regression,

00:55:16.780 --> 00:55:23.860
that's all the level we're teaching right now.

00:55:23.860 --> 00:55:24.860
Thank you.

00:55:24.860 --> 00:55:28.260
Another question I was just copying over from Slido.

00:55:28.260 --> 00:55:35.899
Somebody had asked, how does this compare to platforms like Datacamp?

00:55:35.899 --> 00:55:41.179
Favorably.

00:55:41.179 --> 00:55:47.179
We're really focused on that cohort interaction, that human interaction, creating essentially

00:55:47.179 --> 00:55:51.260
a de facto community of practice amongst the students with their mentor, empowering that

00:55:51.260 --> 00:55:54.500
to continue within the company afterwards.

00:55:54.500 --> 00:56:00.820
The motivation and the engagement, from what I've seen, is night and day different.

00:56:00.820 --> 00:56:06.020
People are really motivated by social pressures and also the identity that they build by engaging

00:56:06.020 --> 00:56:08.379
in a group that's learning data science.

00:56:08.379 --> 00:56:14.139
So I think Datacamp is, and platforms like it, are really great tools for people who

00:56:14.139 --> 00:56:20.580
are enthusiastic and motivated, have time to spare, self-learners.

00:56:20.580 --> 00:56:21.820
And I know people who are like that.

00:56:21.820 --> 00:56:22.820
I'm like that too.

00:56:23.540 --> 00:56:26.699
But I'm not like that when things get busy or hectic or whatnot.

00:56:26.699 --> 00:56:33.300
And what I see is engagement does drop off if you don't have that group of people who

00:56:33.300 --> 00:56:34.300
are pushing you through.

00:56:34.300 --> 00:56:36.820
And that's what we're trying to provide here.

00:56:36.820 --> 00:56:44.699
So I do think that you will notice a difference, but I don't really feel that comfortable talking

00:56:44.699 --> 00:56:47.300
about check comparisons.

00:56:47.300 --> 00:56:51.020
Thank you.

